{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639427"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:05:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:05:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17770"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17770"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75824"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17770"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61337"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2175"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24470"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75824"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of pelvic pain and abnormal vaginal bleeding. She reports a sensation of pelvic fullness and pressure on her bladder, as well as experiencing pain during intercourse. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pelvic examination reveals a palpable mass in the adnexal region. Imaging reveals an abnormal mass in the ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ovarian cyst","Uterine fibroid","Endometriosis","Ovarian tumour","Pelvic inflammatory disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of pelvic pain, abnormal vaginal bleeding, and a sensation of pelvic fullness, along with imaging findings of an ovarian mass, suggests the presence of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian tumour\u003C/strong\u003E. Ovarian tumours can be benign or malignant, and further evaluation, including tumour markers and possibly surgical exploration, would be necessary to determine the nature of the mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian cysts\u003C/strong\u003E can also present with pelvic pain and fullness, but they are typically benign and may resolve spontaneously. The chronicity and associated symptoms in this case make a tumour more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine fibroids\u003C/strong\u003E often cause abnormal bleeding and pelvic pressure, but they are associated with uterine enlargement rather than an isolated ovarian mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pelvic pain and dyspareunia, but it is less likely to present with a distinct ovarian mass on imaging unless there is an endometrioma, which would have a different clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic inflammatory disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents with acute pelvic pain, fever, and cervical motion tenderness. It is less likely to cause a chronic mass in the ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ovarian masses can present with pelvic pain, pressure symptoms, and abnormal bleeding.","Imaging is crucial in identifying ovarian abnormalities and guiding further management.","Differential diagnoses for ovarian masses includes benign and malignant conditions."],"references":["Matulonis UA, Sood AK, Fallowfield L, Howitt BE, Sehouli J, Karlan BY. Ovarian cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Aug 25;2:16061. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.61. PMID: 27558151; PMCID: PMC7290868.","Merritt, M.A., Abe, S.K., Islam, M.R. et al. Reproductive factors and risk of epithelial ovarian cancer: results from the Asia Cohort Consortium. Br J Cancer (2024). https://doi.org/10.1038/s41416-024-02924-z","Stewart C, Ralyea C, Lockwood S. Ovarian Cancer: An Integrated Review. Semin Oncol Nurs. 2019 Apr;35(2):151-156. doi: 10.1016/j.soncn.2019.02.001. Epub 2019 Mar 11. PMID: 30867104."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17770"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61337"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T20:30:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T20:30:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10484"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75824"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synony